v5.0.0

üö® Breaking Change

This release fixes an inconsistency in path behavior for single artifact downloads by ID. If you're downloading single artifacts by ID, the output path may change.

What Changed

Previously, single artifact downloads behaved differently depending on how you specified the artifact:

  • By name: name: my-artifact ‚Üí extracted to path/ (direct)
  • By ID: artifact-ids: 12345 ‚Üí extracted to path/my-artifact/ (nested)

Now both methods are consistent:

  • By name: name: my-artifact ‚Üí extracted to path/ (unchanged)
  • By ID: artifact-ids: 12345 ‚Üí extracted to path/ (fixed - now direct)

Migration Guide

‚úÖ No Action Needed If:
  • You download artifacts by name
  • You download multiple artifacts by ID
  • You already use merge-multiple: true as a workaround
‚ö†Ô∏è Action Required If:

You download single artifacts by ID and your workflows expect the nested directory structure.

Before v5 (nested structure):

- uses: actions/download-artifact@v4
  with:
    artifact-ids: 12345
    path: dist
# Files were in: dist/my-artifact/

Where my-artifact is the name of the artifact you previously uploaded

Original issue description:

> Instructions for Engineering Team: Falsification Tests for Z Framework-Nuclear Synergies Hypothesis
> Hypothesis Statement
> The hypothesis posits synergies between the Z Framework and nuclear stability models, specifically:
> 	‚Ä¢	Nuclear magic numbers (e.g., 2, 8, 20, 28, 50, 82, 126 for protons Z or neutrons N) align with curvature minima in the discrete domain form ( Z = n(\Delta_n / \Delta_{\max}) ), where ( n = A ) (mass number, Z + N), ( \Delta_n = \kappa(n) = d(n) \cdot \ln(n+1) / e^2 ) (d(n) is the number of divisors of n), and ( \Delta_{\max} ) is bounded by ( e^2 \approx 7.389 ).
> 	‚Ä¢	Tetrahedral packings (tetrahedral numbers: 1, 4, 10, 20, 35, 56, 84, 120, 165, 220) partially overlap with magic-related structures, enhancing stability predictions via geodesic resolution ( \theta‚Äô(n, k) = \phi \cdot ((n \bmod \phi)/\phi)^k ) with ( k \approx 0.3 ), yielding ~15% density improvement in stability ‚Äúislands‚Äù (95% CI [14.6%, 15.4%]).
> 	‚Ä¢	5D helical embeddings show Pearson correlations ( r \approx 0.93 ) (p < 10^{-10}) between zeta chain attributes and binding energy contours.
> 	‚Ä¢	This enables predictions for islands of stability (e.g., beyond N=120) with <0.01% error in prime-like gaps.
> Falsification would occur if: (1) kappa values for magic/double-magic nuclides are not significantly lower than non-magic; (2) geodesic enhancements show no density boost or negative/insignificant correlations; (3) tetrahedral alignments lack statistical significance; (4) 5D embeddings yield low correlations (<0.5) with binding energies or decay rates.
> All tests must route numerical operations through DiscreteZetaShift instances (from domain.py) for zeta chain computations, ensuring curvature-based resolutions. Use mpmath for precision (dps=50). Perform pre-computation reflections on zeta attributes (e.g., z, D, E, ‚Ä¶, O) to assess invariants, but report only in internal logs.
> Step 1: Data Acquisition
> 	‚Ä¢	Download the Atomic Mass Evaluation (AME2020) dataset as CSV from Kaggle (e.g., https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/iitm21f1003401/nuclear-binding-energy or similar AME files). 10 This provides Z, N, A, binding energy per nucleon (BE/A), and stability indicators (half-life) for ~3000 nuclides up to A‚âà300.
> 	‚Ä¢	If needed, supplement with IAEA NUBASE2020 data (https://www-nds.iaea.org/amdc/) for half-lives and decay modes. 12 
> 	‚Ä¢	Compile lists:

`--gpu-type "A30, H100_PCIe"` *(OPTIONAL)* : Only run the test stages on the specified GPU types. Examples: "A30, H100_PCIe". Note: Does **NOT** update GitHub check status.

`--test-backend "pytorch, cpp"` *(OPTIONAL)* : Skip test stages which don't match the specified backends. Only support [pytorch, cpp, tensorrt, triton]. Examples: "pytorch, cpp" (does not run test stages with tensorrt or triton backend). Note: Does **NOT** update GitHub pipeline status.

`--only-multi-gpu-test ` *(OPTIONAL)* : Only run the multi-GPU tests. Note: Does **NOT** update GitHub check status.

`--disable-multi-gpu-test ` *(OPTIONAL)* : Disable the multi-GPU tests. Note: Does **NOT** update GitHub check status.

`--post-merge ` *(OPTIONAL)* : Run the L0 post-merge pipeline instead of the ordinary L0 pre-merge pipeline.

`--extra-stage "H100_PCIe-TensorRT-Post-Merge-1, xxx"` *(OPTIONAL)* : Run the ordinary L0 pre-merge pipeline and specified test stages. Examples: --extra-stage "H100_PCIe-TensorRT-Post-Merge-1, xxx".

`--detailed-log ` *(OPTIONAL)* : Enable flushing out all logs to the Jenkins console. This will significantly increase the log volume and may slow down the job.

`--debug ` *(OPTIONAL)* : **Experimental feature**. Enable access to the CI container for debugging purpose. Note: Specify exactly one stage in the `stage-list` parameter to access the appropriate container environment. Note: Does **NOT** update GitHub check status.
